  "timeframe": "1H → 5M → 1M → 30S",
  "market_context": "On the hourly chart, GBP/USD takes out the previous hour's low and closes back inside the range, establishing the previous hour high as the easy draw on liquidity for the new hourly candle.",
  "key_observation": "After the hourly sweeps prior hour low and reclaims, the 5-minute leaves a respected fair value gap; the new hour opens, retraces into the FVG, then displaces upward, providing a 30-second FVG entry targeting the previous hour high.",
  "analysis_steps": [
    "Step 1: On the 1H chart, identify that price took the previous hour low and closed back inside, making the previous hour high the obvious draw on liquidity.",
    "Step 2: Drop to the 5-minute chart to confirm the previous hour low sweep and observe price closing back into range, leaving a 5-minute fair value gap.",
    "Step 3: As the new hourly candle opens, observe price respecting the 5-minute FVG and anticipate a draw from the FVG up to the previous hour high.",
    "Step 4: Drop to the 30-second chart to find displacement off the FVG, creating a smaller 30-second fair value gap for a precise entry.",
    "Step 5: Enter on the 30-second FVG, targeting the previous hour high; a second 30-second FVG forms, is respected, and price reaches the target.",
    "Step 6: Alternatively, on the 1-minute chart, consider entering at the 5-minute FVG with stop below the mean threshold of the order block, requiring at least 2R to the prior hour high."
  ],
  "outcome": "Price reached the previous hour high target after respecting the fair value gaps on the lower timeframes; trade played out successfully.",
  "lessons": "Higher-timeframe draw on liquidity (previous hour high) combined with lower-timeframe fair value gap respect allows precise execution; the same fractal logic works whether using 30-second, 1-minute, or 15-minute as the execution timeframe.",
